text: Bale's role looks amaizng here and its important to say this loud : I'm tired of people being ignorant, when it comes to the amazing, pure Bale's acting talent, the ability to enter the psyche and emotions of the characters - and he does it here, fantastically. It's like saying that Gary Oldman should not get an Oscar for Churchill - he was also totally 'disguised', but that's what total acting is all about - you are changing externally and internally, every acting job is a dress-up, evey actor has some make up, disguise - more or less. And you know that with authentic characters, you always have to externally change. Just like Nicole Kidman turned into Virginia Woolf, but does the ''dress-up'' deprive her role of genius in showing the emotions of the character? No, because both things  - physicality and emotions - matter in acting and Bale is great in this trailer, you can tell, thats why we talking Oscars. Bale is someone like Daniel Day-Lewis, he goes all in, he is an outstanding actor.

text: Regarding the beginning of this trailer, you have to be one hell of a fucking idiot if you think this is how this arrangement took place. It's very clear Dick Cheney wanted to be President from the beginning, but realizing he wouldn't win, used Dubya as the face of the campaign when he really was the one who was going to be in charge. I think it's a bit disingenuous for anyone to think Dubya actually came to Cheney thinking that he would be an asset as a VP candidate for his campaign and making him such an incredible deal to join it. I feel sorry for anyone who is dumb enough to believe the story this movie is trying to sell you, but many Americans and foreigners will, unfortunately. I've already lost any hope for this movie being good. The average bumpkin also isn't going to realize that the War on Terror wasn't about trying to end terrorism, it was about showing other countries that the US can still project its force and control geopolitics. text: Watching this Truly Brilliant movie today on Independence Day--just Excellent. Love the "Hallmark" Style The End Commercial in the middle-CLASSIC!--the speech Colin Powell gave to The United Nations played by Tyler Perry (very accurately), showed Mr. Powell's inner objection. I remember all of these events as many others do. While clearly the Iraq War was about Oil and a bad move--Mr. Cheney and President Bush did keep their Promise to the American People. The last Interview I also remember very well--He did what we asked him to do. Do I support torture? Hell NO! Do I support War? NEVER! I do however believe our Country was attacked that day. This movie brilliantly shows the BS of Washington and it's overstuffed Bureaucracy and how it functions or doesn't. It shows the way The White House "Spins" the Truth and renames it all the time. Most if not all of this is so true. Is this movie funny? It is brutal in your face reality. And it is important that this film got made. Christian Bale= Outstanding. Amy Adams also did such a great job being the Powerhouse behind the man. As so many women truly are. And Cheney's daughter Mary having her private life just put out there for all the world to judge and take apart. So awful. Sam Rockwell did a bang up job playing President George Bush. But while I disagree with President Bush on some things, I will always be grateful to him for doing what Americans needed-to be protected. Iraq however; that's a different fight that was never ours. America does not own the Middle East. We should probably rebuild our own Country first. This movie, "Vice", asks a very important question regarding Absolute Power of The US President. This is so relevant because we are now on a road where Checks and Balances do not even exist anymore. This is so bad for our Country.
